analog_response: I was in my world history class in high school, and we were debating abortion for some reason. I explained why I supported the right to have an abortion, and then a boy who was considered smarter and more popular than me said "Well, as a Roman Catholic, I believe abortion is wrong." Suddenly, everyone seemed to switch over to his side, even though he didn't provide any reasons other than his personal religious beliefs, and I felt very much shut out.

I have always been called a socialist or communist by Trump supporters whenever I explain to them that I do not believe people should be left to starve and/or die if they cannot support themselves. I believe that the purpose of government is to serve the people who they govern, and to take care of them because no person should die/struggle. if they lack finances. Trump supporters have always seen this as some sort of totalitarianism mindset and it is extremely frustrating that people have no compassion for others.
I felt frustrated and awkward when we held vastly different opinions.
I felt misunderstood by others when my manager at my old job refused to pay me my wages I earned. I feel like they did not understand that I need to pay rent and that they were being rude.

My wife and I agree on most things, but there are occasionally times when I feel misunderstood when I try to voice an opinion that differs from hers. This morning we were discussing a TV show that she likes and I only tolerate. I tried multiple times to describe the reasons I don't especially care for the show - my reasons were absolutely subjective, a reflection of my personal preferences, but my wife insisted on trying to argue our difference in terms of objective facts about the show (which was never my intention or reason for disagreeing with her about the show), rather than simply acknowledging our different opinions.

I once voiced my opinions to someone about God and religion.  I feel that God exists but I don't  necessarily define God the way Christianity defines God.  In fact I sort of feel that both religion and science fail in describing God or even the mysteries of life. There is still so much really don't know about either. I tried explaining this to someone who was Christian and they thought of me as being atheist because my definition of God and the origin of life did not follow what they believed from their religion.
When I was discussing whether or not we should be wearing masks

A time that comes to mind is when I was discussing politics with my parent and feelings toward covid and how it was handled. I know everyone has their own opinion but I just couldn't understand how they could support Trump with the way it was handled even when they were terrified of the pandemic like I was. But I also believe that you can't change someone's view even if it doesn't match yours.
At work, another employee advised that they did not believe in masking and refused to wear a mask. I said that it was just to help everyone.
Anytime I try to have a conversation with most of the people in my extended family. They're republicans who don't know how to have a rational political discussion.
It happened a lot with my ex over parenting issues, specifically over corporal punishment. No matter what I said, he never understood why I am completely opposed.

I often have this feeling at work. My supervisor parrots right wing talking points and expects me to agree with them, which puts me in an uncomfortable situation since she's my superior. Often the things she says are borderline racist, xenophobic, and conspiratorial. I'm in a constant state of alienation. The latest is the Supreme Court confirmation hearings, where she describes Jackson-Brown as someone who gives lenient sentences and doesn't give firm answers, though she is "articulate".

I was speaking to an aunt about problems I was facing and how these negatively held views that people have for people like me  affect me a great deal. She was unsympathetic and almost made it seem like it was my fault.
we met on common ground

I have this problem quite often with my dad as we exist on complete opposite sides of the political spectrum and rather than try to understand my point of view, he often dismisses me as "too young" and "lacking common sense." This always makes me frustrated because he doesn't even try to understand my opinion and this creates a disconnect between the two of us where I never feel like he understands me or wants to even try to.

I held a pro choice opinion and was being constantly harassed by another person for being a baby killer. I have never, and am not qualified to perform abortions. No matter what I said they ignored all rational arguments or conversations, instead saying the same thing over and over again. It was very frustrating because I saw no logical argument or defense from their side besides their continual statement saying that THEY were not a baby killer like I was.

When I came out as gay to my family and they had a hard time understanding it and comprehending it. They continuously said things like, "I don't understand how you can be that way". When I tried to explain it to them they did not really listen to the things I was saying.
I did not feel understood by my father because I was very much for more socialism and he saw that as pure evil.  It made for a very uncomfortable situation with him.

My mom and I hold different political beliefs. Oftentimes, she will shut the conversation down when I talk about information she immediately believes to be wrong. This overflows into my general life, where she believes everything she does is right and if I am not doing something similar I am wrong. We often get into arguments over the phone because she thinks it is awful if I do not have the time to speak to her when she wants me to. I think it is reasonable that I do not always have the time nor want to speak with her. If she is busy or doesn't want to speak to me, there is no argument. It ends up with me feeling bad because I know she has no support otherwise.
This was a time where we were in class and another student and I disagreed on what we should do on a project

In my family they are all conservatives so when i started to make up my own mind about things i found i leaned more liberal and they just do not understand my views on just about everything and do not make attempts to learn.

That's everyday living in OK. Just yesterday i was talking to a coworker about Ukraine and he though we should not help them. I totally disagreed and said we should send them weapons and other aid and he totally disagreed. Like, what? How could you disagree i felt like he was just trolling, but he was serious. I told him 10 good reasons why we should but he did not agree at all.

I'm not sure if I've had this experience. My sister has, though, and she recounted this story to me about how she as trying to convince our aunt and uncle to vote no on a marriage amendment on our state that would limit marriage to heterosexual couples. The way that she was leading my aunt had her almost convinced, until my uncle said, "Yeah, we'll vote no, but only if it guarantees marriage is between a man and a woman." It was at that moment that she realized there was no point trying to discuss the issue further. They didn't understand her and would not agree with her.

One time I was trying to explain my view on gay marriage to a family member. I listened to their side of the argument, but when I tried to explain my stance on why it should be allowed, they refused to listen. It was very frustrating to be expected to listen to them, but not to have my point heard as well.
I felt misunderstood by my mom about being pro choice.

A couple of years ago, an acquaintance, who happens to be a staunch Republican, asked my what I thought the Democratic party had to offer the country.  I explained my position clearly and concisely but at the end of the conversation this person still did not understand my position.
Sadly, I cant think of a time. But I do have a lot of differing opinions from my brother and my dad. Im usually more neutral to things.

When I was trying to explain to a coworker of mine my struggles as a woman of color and the obstacles I had to get through to get to where I am now. He was very adamant that we don't experience the same kind of prejudices he experiences as a straight white man and how culture nowadays are very quick to cancel him.

I felt misunderstood by my boss once when she tried to talk to me about a political issue. She is Democrat and assumed that because I'm lesbian and a Democrat, my political opinions on a certain issue were a certain way, but I actually felt the opposite. I didn't want to create any kind of disagreement, and I don't like talking politics at work, so once I realized that my opinions might cause an argument, I toned them down and changed the subject. She seemed confused by me. She had stereotypical views about me based on my identity, but I don't always agree with the Democrats on every single issue and I resent when other people assume I do.
when i told my friend to get vaccinated but he would not listen
I felt misunderstood when talking about politics for the 2020 election because people who voted for Trump wouldn't't listen to reasons why I chose not to vote for him or accept when he lost.

not to long ago my aunt and i were having a discussion about abortion. she was saying she didnt believe in it and wants them to make them illegal. i was trying to explain to her that some people who get raped or are too young and get assulted shouldn't have to carry a fetus just because someone else thinks its wrong
I was having a political discussion with one of my friends and they completely understood my opinion because it was different from theirs.

One time I had a conversation with my step-dad about the covid-19 vaccine. His opinion was that the vaccine was not researched enough, and developed too quickly and is therefore unsafe. He also believed that it should not be a requirement for children to have this vaccination to go to school because it is "unconstitutional". My response was that the vaccine had been FDA approved and that children already have several vaccinations that must be done before entering school. I felt very frustrated because instead of looking at facts that I was stating and taking them into consideration, it seemed like he just wanted to be "right" for the sake of it and because he is older than me.

I work at a Labor-Zionist summer camp, and I hold Zionist beliefs.  However, a majority of the staff that works there are anti-Zionist.  

We were having a discussion on the necessity of Israel in the world, and I could not get any common ground with the other staff.  I felt dismissed, and not understood.

I was in a philosophy class and we were discussing deontological ethics. There was only one other student who had any interest, and they seemed to regard me as being morally repugnant because we had differing opinions on ethics and how they originate. Specifically, this person believed that without an outside factor determining what i right you could not have a logical basis for morality. Because we disagreed on the existence of a God, in other words, I could not be moral. It was a pretty long and sometimes ugly debate that we never resolved.

Years ago at my community college in a sociology class on women, the teacher took a poll to see how many people identified as feminist, and it was just me and one other girl who raised their hands. I felt really perplexed because this seemed so odd to me, so at the end of the semester I asked that we redo the poll and more people raised their hands but even after all that education and clarifying that there was nothing bad about identifying as a feminist, it was maybe half the class that raised their hands, if that.
any topic about trump and his brainwashed supporters

My husband does not handle change well at all and thinks things should just stay the same to make the world an easier place to live. Recently, we were discussing employment issues in our country and he (also a manager) thinks that too much has changed too fast and that is the problem with this country as it encourages people to not want to work. I told him things aren't changing fast enough - wage increases, better working conditions, work from home opportunity, etc - and that is driving people away from more traditional and service industry related jobs. He told me I (as a person seeking a job) have no idea what I am talking about and he (as a manager) has seen it all. I definitely do not feel understood by him.

I had a job interviewing people about their opinions on local political leaders and an interviewee kept asking me my opinion about the upcoming presidental election. I told him I was on the clock and for all intents and purposes I didn't have an opinion about the upcoming presidental election. He said I was a Biden voter and tried to end the interview early.

I was talking about pronouns with someone and they didn't understand the need for someone to have to always define their pronouns. I get that it is kind of repetitive, but I see the importance of having to make people aware of your background or preferences.

I am very liberal and have a very conservative family so this is a very familiar feeling to me. It's definitely most prominent when issues about abortion come up — to me, the right to an abortion is fundamental and ought to be extended, and this makes some members of my family think that I am an evil person.

I felt I was not understood because we had different political views about Joe Biden and Donald Trump. We both had extremely different views on political candidates and democrat versus republican views.

I experience this a little regularly online. I often feel misunderstood immediately when someone decides to become argumentative with something, and its typically over my values and beliefs over human rights and how everyone should be treated with integrity and decency.

I remember telling a friend about how I disliked the class of a professor and dropped it after the first class, but it seems that they didn't understand my point about why I found the professor's behavior undesirable. I didn't feel comfortable with the jokes and personal information the professor shared, but my friend didn't get it.

This would be the time I spoke up against a coworker after he made a remark about foreigners taking up all of americas resources and shouldnt be allowed to be here. I reprimanded him because I hold completely oppsite views and then he became irate and offended while trying to make believe I was being naive for having different views.

When talking about the causes of homelessness I have felt misunderstood because, while I do try to lead with compassion, I have practical reasons to support for more social support of those that find themselves in that situation regardless of their personal merit or the issues of social justice.  I think people, in general, do not take a practical approach and are not used to taking into account multiple perspectives at the same time.  It is difficult to go beyond stereotypical misunderstandings or prejudices.

when discussing something that upset me, an athiest, my religious mom discounted my feelings and said that I was not acting Christian. It was difficult because I know the rejection of her ideology would be upsetting but I do not hold that ideology.

I recently had a conversation with my husband that was supposed to be neutral but when race was brought into the conversation, he said, "Everyone hates white people now." I am Asian and this was an ignorant statement due to the qualifier of "now" ... it shows a complete lack of perspective of minority people who would be accurate in saying "have always" and dont have the luxury of say "now"

my boyfriend doesn't understand how much i support abortion. he is pretty anti-abortion on most cases even though he claims to be pro-choice. he doesn't seem to understand the necessity to have access to abortion and be able to get one for ANY reason as a woman.

I felt that way with a friend I had a few years ago. I couldnt seem to get him to understand why I felt the way about certain political and social situations. We had differing political opinions and I feel like that is where our issues started. It only got worse from there to the point of where I no longer wanted to be friends with him. At first I thought we could be friends even though he had voted for trump but as time went on I found that he had deeper issues that I could not hope to improve. I found that he was racist, sexist and just overall had very different views from me and was not open to changing. When there was a language barrier.

I can often feel this way when speaking with my own family. We hold very different political beliefs and I don't think we'll ever fully understand each others' sides fully or convince the other side to consider our opinions.
My mother doesn't understand why healthcare for all would be beneficial for the whole country, including herself.
A time  I felt understood was when someone assumed I was a goody two shoes about following instruction
I did not feel understood by a guy I met at a ski resort because he believed in God and I don't.

Literally every Christmas. My uncle, who hosts our Christmas Eve dinner, is a loon. Deeply Republican. He's out there. He still says "colored" in reference to black people. So yeah, he doesn't understand me. We argue every single year.

I honestly can't think of a time. The closest think I can thing I can think of is an old friend of mine stating Nonbinary people are mentally sick or fake. I have a spouse that is nonbinary themselves.

I did not feel understood by my boyfriend when we had differing opinions about how to take care of the house and the chores around the house. I did not feel understood by my friend. We were voting for different candidates in the 2020 presidential election. She acted as if I was a bad person for voting for the candidate I chose. This made me feel very misunderstood as a person.
When I disagreed with another person regarding politics in 2020 I felt diminished and also felt that my opinion did not matter.
I have a friend that's pro life. I am pro choice. We don't discuss this topic because neither of us can understand the other's point of view.

My neighbors kept putting their political signs along my property line and didn't understand why it upset me. They refused to move the signs, saying they were on their side of the property line, and if I'm too embarrassed to put up my own signs supporting my candidate, that's my problem.

I am the lone non-Republican on my mother's side of the family and I do not understand these people nor do they understand me. When Covid first came around and Trump was still in office my uncle started talking about how we needed to pray for the President because we didn't want him to get sick and I refused to participate, the reaction from some family members made me feel sad and angry and hopeless. These people are my family and I grew up loving and admiring them and now they fly Trump flags and act like Trump is a saint who can do no wrong, when they used to say that "dissent is patriotic" and "no one is perfect" and I just don't know how to reconcile these things. It makes me cry just writing about it. I don't know what is happening to people, and I don't know how to get through to anyone anymore. I just keep my thoughts and feelings to myself because nothing is good enough for anyone anymore, and no matter what my thoughts and opinions are someone will hate me for them, and attack me for them.

During the impeachment fiasco of Trump when the report came out, I spoke with my son-in-law about the report. He had read only some of it and I had read the entire report. He would not see it even though it was obvious and written down and corroborated in the report. He still wanted to believe in Trump and swallow any amount of garbage that Trump and his cronies spewed out. It was frustrating.

I currently disagree with some of my friends on the issue of transgender athletes in sports. I support transgender rights in general, and my opinions are fairly nuanced.  However, I don't want to be misunderstood, so I don't speak my opinions on this topic.
The last time I tried to talk to my next-door neighbor about Trump. She absolutely loves him and I can’t stand him. No matter what I say she still thinks he’s awesome. I find it very confusing.
My boyfriend was an anti-vaxxer but I was not. My grandfather died from coronavirus and I feel like he didn't understand the impact that had on me.

I thought that maybe about 10,000 people genuinely believed that Gucci Mane was a clone when he came out of prison. My friends thought I was being absurd but they were understimating the amount of stupid people in the world.

I felt like I wasn't understood once because I felt differently about them on abortion rights. The other person was pro-life, and I was pro-choice. The other person ended our friendship over this.
Talking to a highly conservative person about LGBT rights as they refused to let me speak, kept interrupting, and had false “facts” that they heard from unreliable internet sources.

There was a time when I tried to explain why it is best and in good manners and respect to address the elderly,  as "sir" or "ma'am".  The millennial did not agree with me and chose to call the elderly by their first name and could not understand who some of the elderly spoke rudely to them.
It's typically been on being vaccinated vs not being vaccinated. There's lots of times where that tends to happen.

I did not feel understood by my uncle during a conversation about Black Lives Matter (BLM). I recall a time when I was in the military and did not feel understood by my supervisor.  She held a strong set of beliefs about her religion and felt the need to impose her beliefs on her subordinates.  I did not feel this was right and protested against such behavior.

My dad and I both love history, but he's lived longer than I have, and has a personal connection with world events that I've only read about. We argue a lot, and it's practically an act of love. But sometimes when we talk about events like the Vietnam War or the Cold War, we don't understand each other. He understands how it felt at the time, but I only know the results. One time I spent the night crying in my room because we disagreed on why and how the My Lai Massacre should be taught in schools. For him, it was a contentious event that is controversial to address. For me, not teaching it is indicative of America's propagandistic approach to historical pedagogy. But it felt more like he didn't understand that my concerns were about more than one event, but my entire historical education, and how I felt lied to by my educators.

I was trying to explain to someone in my group that people in general are not unemployed because they make enough from the government stimulus to stay home and because they were lazy. The person was so determined to be right that she just kept talking over me every time I tried to bring some discussion or facts to the table.
I really don't like telling about my personal life. And hat is there to tell? They didn't understand my position and there was no changing their mind.

The last time I felt like I didn't understand someoene who didn't hold a similar belief to my was my old boss. I was talking about harm reduction, and the work I was doing in drug policy, to prevent non-violent drug offenders from going to prison and getting rehabiliated, and he calmly commented that he didn't care if all the junkies in the world died. It was horrible, and I felt really separte from him at that moment.

My father voted for Trump and would not even listen to me in regards to immigration policy. No amount of explaining the life the immigrants were leaving or advocating for how their diversity could help the US, made any difference to him. It's like he wasn't even listening or trying to debate, just to talk over me and state his points.

It happened yesterday. I went to the hospital ER, because of a very painful medical problem I have been having for awhile now. I have been treated with it, and it did go away last year.  The doctor wanted to prescribe me medication that did not work for me in the past.  I tried to explain to her my reason why I wanted something else.  She wouldnt budge from her choice, so she compromised by adding an additional medicine.

My husband and I disagree strongly on our political views, it can be extremely frustrating when talking about political topics or candidates especially when we are both very stubborn in our views and it ends up just turning into a topic we do not discuss often.

A time when I had a difference of opinion and did not feel understood by someone else was when talking about parenting styles. I personally believe in "gentle parenting" and natural consequences as opposed to corporal punishment. When explaining this to a family member I did not think they understood that children can learn without fear and/or pain.
I disagreed with a friend regarding whether or not people should be forced to talk to people about options of what to do in regards to an unplanned pregnancy if they want an abortion.

It was during a meeting at work.  I was trying to explain to my co-worker why I had to leave early from work, due to my child being sick and needing me to pick her up from school.  My co-worker argued with me back and forth about why women always use their kids as an excuse to leave work early and how he felt victimized as a single man.  I did everything within reason to discuss and make him understand my opinion on the matter without getting upset with him or causing a scene.

I think that protecting the innocence of children at all costs only harms them in the long run. My mother disagrees with that sentiment and does not understand my point of view. She thinks they should be protected from harsh realities until they are forced to face them unprepared, on their own.

Everytime I talk politics with my one friend it's super annoying because he always wants to be the centrist/devils advocate, to the extent that it doesn't feel like he's even listening to what I'm saying, it feels like he just wants to disagree no matter what I say. I stopped talking politics with him because I feel like I'm not being heard. I don't need him to agree with everything I say or anything, just to listen to my points and then respond however he truly feels, not just 'what about the other side?'

I was having an argument about abortion with a friend after a party at my house one night. What had started out as a simple discussion about our stances on the issue had gotten very out of hand. The person I was discussing with refused to believe that I wanted to reduce the total number of abortions, because in his mind, if you believed something was wrong, you must want it to be illegal. He even went so far as to say that a woman who would have an abortion did not deserve to live. I never felt so out of touch with someone on an issue I felt like we fundamentally agreed on, that abortions should be avoided.
I disagreed with a cow-worker about the role of cloud computing in our industry. I felt they didn't understand the point I was making.

Once, my cousin was going on about politics and saying how both sides are bad, and the typical enlightened centrism rhetoric. And I told him while I agree in principle that politicians of all parties can be corrupt and tell lies to get votes, that I could not afford to throw a vote away -- either by not voting or voting independent -- because I am both queer and a woman, and I have to vote for people to stay in power who support my rights, freedoms, and safety. And it was just like I was speaking another language to him, he couldn't comprehend that because he's a privilege straight white man who never thinks about these things.

I had a conversation with a coworker about the Black lives matter movement.  He claimed that Black lives matter movement was against the police and wanted to eliminate police departments.  I tried to explain to him that movement want more accountability of the police and criminal justice reform.
I was talking to my friend and she didn't understand where I was coming from or how I think because I didnt care for hating on republicans or people who voted Trump.

I did not feel understood by my parents when my son came out as bisexual. His partner is non binary and my father in particular kept wanting to call them a "she" when I kept reminding him that their pronouns were "they/them". He was doing it on purpose and I had to have a talk with my parents about hurting my son's feelings, which I know was not their intention but was a byproduct.

My mom and I talked about abortion. I explained to her why I supported abortion. She ignored my viewpoints and said that abortion is still wrong. I told her that she should listen to my viewpoints and understand my perspective. However, she refused and said that I was still wrong.
I am constantly feeling uncomfortable with many of my family members, old friends regarding of political events, especially since the last president (Trump) and now as war erupted in Ukraine.

I realized my friends I was living with were trump supporters, as far as I understand it. This was incredibly disappointing to me that they are this way because they are also members of the lgbt community along with me. I felt devalued by them and that they were in the wrong,

A good friend of mine is very upset about Lia Thomas winning a first-place medal in a swimming event and feels like she had advantages over her competitors. It bothered me that he would rather hang onto his anger than listen to reason or understand the reality of the situation.

I recently had a discussion with my friend Torbjorn, who is from Switzerland, about media outlets. He asked me if I subscribed to the NY Time and the Washington Post. I told him I did and then he said I needed to also read the Washington Times so that I could get a conservative's point of view on things. I do not think he understands that I do not care about conservatives' points of view. My opinion is that they are not usually good people any more.
I posted the George Floyd video when it first came out.  I had a friend write on my post that "All Lives Matter".  I was so completely shocked at how insensitive she was.

When Trump was elected, I was devastated. My very conservative then-boyfriend kindly said, "I'm sorry your candidate lost." I didn't have the heart or the words to try to explain to him that it wasn't that "my candidate" lost, it was that I was grieving and terrified for our country because Trump won.

analog_response: I was misunderstood by family when we disagreed on the vaccine and risks of covid. I got the vaccine and was sheltering in place for health reasons and to help stop the spread. They thought that I was being a sheep and scared.

Recently, my brother and I disagreed on what NATO (and the international community) should do to assist Ukraine. I held NATO should establish a no-fly zone and directly supply weapons to the Ukrainians. My brother disagreed, believing this would lead to WWIII and nuclear fallout. As such, despite knowing each other for all our lives, I felt misunderstood by my brother; like we were strangers. Part of this has to do with the fact that I thought he would agree with me. So often, we have the same opinions (especially politically). Since we did not this time, it came across as incredibly jarring for me.

A time when I did not feel understood by another person because I held a different opinion from them was recently when talking about workers' unions and the importance of having them.  The person I was talking to only thinks that unions steal workers' money and protect lazy and bad workers.  I was trying to tell the person about the good things that come from unions, and this person stopped listening, interrupted me, and started to become condescending and stated that "you just don't understand these types of things."
I disagreed with an older man about abortion. He believed that humanity began at conception and abortion is murder. We could not even talk after that.

I had the feeling about being misunderstood by a person that felt Donald Trump had made improvements to the Department of Veterans Affairs. I stated , correctly, that many of the things Trump took credit for started under Obama or were simply untrue. He refused to believe this was the case took an attitude that he simply could not believe anything I told him.
I'm a progressive and the majority of my family are conservatives. We've disagreed on pretty much everything and I have very little connection to any of them

I felt I was not understood by somebody when I told them that immigrants coming to America is not a bad thing and there are positives to this as most people in American are immigrants from a long time ago. But the person strongly held the belief that immigrants would increase crime rates.

I have felt like I wasn't understood by my hispanic side of the family when I've tried to explain to them the American views on marijuana, and also how I feel that alcohol is just as dangerous as any other addictive chemical.

I was talking to my adult son about censorship, specifically if news or social media posts should be censored. I explained that I was undecided generally but leaned slightly to favoring some censorship. I listened to his arguments against any kind of censorship. He seemed frustrated with my indecision, as if I was completely for censorship, I don't think he could accept or understand my position was simply undecided.

I was talking to a lady at the park who sat beside me on a bench. We pointed out who our kids were as we watched them play, and she made, what seemed to be at the time a playful observation, of my children's weight, calling them "chubby". I simply agreed and carried on the conversation, but later she pointed out my weight, then questioned me on whether or not I'm going to let them be fat forever, since I'm fat.
